                                                    <comments>
                    <comment id="12740579" author="tmueller" created="Fri, 7 Aug 2009 15:58:10 +0100"  >There are other features that seem to be unused, such as:&lt;br/&gt;
touch, move, copy, and list. Still needed are listFiles and listFolders,&lt;br/&gt;
so we might as well keep list. But we could remove touch, move, and copy&lt;br/&gt;
from the FileSystem interface.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
What do you think? It would simplify implementing a new file system.</comment>
                    <comment id="12740581" author="mreutegg" created="Fri, 7 Aug 2009 16:05:42 +0100"  >+1 for removing unused methods and classes.</comment>
                    <comment id="12740625" author="jukkaz" created="Fri, 7 Aug 2009 17:36:59 +0100"  >+1 To cleaning up the interface.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
Dropping the FileSystem interface entirely might be a bit too drastic for 2.0, but I&amp;#39;d certaily consider doing that in the 3.0 timeframe.</comment>
                    <comment id="12741212" author="stefan@jira" created="Mon, 10 Aug 2009 08:03:57 +0100"  >getRandomAccessOutputStream was used for experimental Lucene support, which however was abandoned for several reasons.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
touch, move et al were used in very early jackrabbit implementations. AFAIK they&amp;#39;re not used anymore.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
+1 for removing unused legacy code.&lt;br/&gt;
</comment>
                    <comment id="12741238" author="jukkaz" created="Mon, 10 Aug 2009 10:02:22 +0100"  >Using fix version 2.0.0 instead of 2.0-alpha7 as the latter release was already tagged.</comment>
